</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="288" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="7.[136,1452,496,1423]" pageId="7" pageNumber="288">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,436,1288,1314]" pageId="7" pageNumber="288">Conservation status:</emphasis>
—So far, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. J. Ling &amp; M. X. Ren" authorityYear="2022" box="[545,813,1288,1314]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Oreocharis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="288" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hainanensis">
<emphasis box="[545,813,1288,1314]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="288">Oreocharis hainanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known from two locations (less than 5 locations) with about 
<geoCoordinate box="[261,323,1324,1350]" degrees="3,000" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="7" pageNumber="288" precision="55" value="3.0">3,000</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[323,401,1324,1350]" degrees="4,000" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="7" pageNumber="288" precision="55" value="-4.0">–4,000</geoCoordinate>
individuals. The populations are under threat due to the limited and fragmented karst habitats, with a very restricted area of occupancy (typically less than 
<quantity box="[799,869,1360,1386]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="288" unit="km" value="20.0">20 km</quantity>
<superScript attach="left" box="[869,877,1360,1374]" fontSize="6" pageId="7" pageNumber="288">2</superScript>
). Therefore, we propose that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="S. J. Ling &amp; M. X. Ren" authorityYear="2022" box="[1204,1371,1360,1386]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Oreocharis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="7" pageNumber="288" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hainanensis">
<emphasis box="[1204,1371,1360,1386]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="288">O. hainanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be considered as Vulnerable (VU C1 and D2) according to the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria (
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN Standards &amp; Petitions Subcommittee" box="[1291,1430,1396,1422]" pageId="7" pageNumber="288" refId="ref5799" refString="IUCN Standards and Petitions Subcommittee (2019) Guidelines for using the IUCN Red List Categories and criteria, version 14. Standards and Petitions Committee, 113 pp." type="book" year="2019">IUCN 2019</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
